{title: The Room At The Top Of The Stairs}
{artist: Cal Smith}
{composer: Written by Lola Jean Dillon}

[C]In the [G]room at the [D7]top of the [G]stairs
We grew up together on the [C]wrong side of the river
And her [G]dream was to make it to [D7]here
Well she [G]won his attention and a [C]place in his mansion
In the [G]room at the [D7]top of the [G]stairs
In that cold lonely mansion lies a [C]lady hot with passion
And a [G]man to busy to [D7]care
When he’s [G]off with his brokers she [C]invites me over
To the [G]room at the [D7]top of the [G]stairs
Lord [C]he’d never believe that these [G]old worn out jeans
Have been thrown across his best velvet [D7]chair
Damned these [G]old cowboy’s blues for [C]wanting to take roots
In the [G]room at the [D7]top of the [G]stairs
As I hide here and wait for him to [C]drive out the gate
Lord my [G]heart is already up [D7]there
And [G]my hands won’t stop shaking at the [C]thought of her aching
In the [G]room at the [D7]top of the [G]stairs
[D7]Damned these [G]old cowboy’s blues for [C]wanting to take roots
In the [G]room at the [D7]top of the [G]stairs